# AEM DAM Expiration Manager - Example Claude Desktop Configuration

This example shows how to configure the AEM DAM Expiration Manager MCP server with Claude Desktop.

## Setup Steps

1. **Build the project:**
   ```bash
   npm install
   npm run build
   ```

2. **Update your Claude Desktop config** (`~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json`):

   ```json
   {
     "mcpServers": {
       "aem-dam-expiration": {
         "command": "node",
         "args": ["/path/to/aem-dam-expiration/dist/index.js"],
         "env": {
           "AEM_AUTHOR_URL": "https://author.your-aem-instance.com",
           "AEM_PUBLISH_URL": "https://publish.your-aem-instance.com",
           "AEM_USERNAME": "your-username",
           "AEM_PASSWORD": "your-password"
         }
       }
     }
   }
   ```

## Environment Variables

- `AEM_AUTHOR_URL`: Full URL to AEM author instance (e.g., https://author.example.com)
- `AEM_PUBLISH_URL`: Full URL to AEM publish instance (e.g., https://publish.example.com)
- `AEM_USERNAME`: Service account or user account with DAM and content access
- `AEM_PASSWORD`: Account password or API token

## Usage in Claude

Once configured, you can interact with the MCP server:

```
Can you find all expired assets in our AEM DAM and tell me which ones are referenced in published pages?

Then for the assets that ARE referenced, extend their expiration by one year.
```

Claude will use the available tools to:
1. List expired assets
2. Check references for each asset
3. Extend expiration for referenced assets
4. Provide you with a summary report

## Security Notes

- Store credentials securely (use service accounts when possible)
- Consider using environment variable files that are not committed to git
- In production, use API tokens instead of user passwords
- Ensure AEM user has appropriate DAM and page query permissions
